div.div:
A graph of 'interface structures as interacting spectrums'can identify missing graphs that are useful to identify, like how a 'function interaction map' can be identified as useful to connect to a 'structure similarity map' when the structure map is incomplete, which indicates comparing it to a more complete graph can identify missing components.
For example, a graph indicating the attributes like 'chirality' of structures like 'substances' is likely to be incomplete and incapable of predicting 'future useful substances' on its own, because it leaves out context like other graphs like 'usage graphs (indicating how and where and why a substance is used, like whether its used in a particular pathway or organ)' and 'interactivity graphs (indicating probable interactions between bio system structures and substances like whether the substance can cross the blood-brain barrier, or substance-substance interactions)' and 'function maps (indicating how functions interact in the bio-system)' and 'causal variable graphs (indicating how structures can cause other structures)' as well as connections between these graphs. Similarly, 'graphs of structural similarities' can be too simple to identify structures like 'limits/thresholds' which differentiate very similar structures.
